body: The seabase tests failed because this code change introduced a regression in the handling of delimited identifiers (such as "_SALT_"). Do not merge until this is reworked.

Thank you for thorough review and valuable feedback. I have addressed all the feedback in the additional commit and also included changes to pick GETN request in executor parent down queue request to drive TopN sort. If the request is GETALL, then TopN sort is not involved.

Please review and merge.

Looks like compGeneral/TEST042 is giving different results?

conversion instructions are usually computed during compile of a query and
then stored in conversion clause. If an instruction of CONV_NOT_SUPPORTED 
shows up in conversion clause at runtime, then need to find out why a supported
instruction was not generated during compile time. That may point to some other
issue related to instruction generation. This happens in exp/exp_fixup.cpp

Some scenarios where instructions are not generated is if expressions are not used
to do a runtime conversion. This could happen if an input value is being moved from app
to cli, or a value is being inserted into a table without the use of expression (like during
bulk load or hive insert).

In the query example of this jira, was an expression used to insert or was instruction being
computed on the fly at runtime?

This change will help in fast computation of conversion instructions but we also need
to find out if there is some other root cause that resulted in this instruction not being
generated at compile time.

Another thing: in addition to conversions, instructions are also computed for comparison
and arithmetic operations.

Response to comments by @zellerh 
1. The code adds NULL to the constructor of many collection objects. On one hand, this is good, as it makes people think, on the other hand I'm not sure it really adds much.
Yes, passing in NULL is the same using the default constructor before. Objects are allocated in the global heap. Currently code calls NACollection constructors with NULL for class variables only if no suitable NAHeap object is available. I would claim this is about a dozen or so instances. In these cases the change does no harm but makes no improvement. It will be a longer term project to create a NAHeap object that could be used in these instances. Mostly these classes are shared across many processes or are required early in the life of a process when NAHeap objects have not been created. For stack variables there are many more instances of using NULL. These are harmless as they would get deallocated when the local variable goes out of scope. I view them as equivalent to numerous NAString stack variables that are created without a heap and are therefore allocated in the global heap. Those are not leaks as I understand that memory is reclaimed when the destructor is called on those objects
1. This is the case discussed in item 1. I don't think they cause problems any worse than now.

I don't quite follow the line of argument in the conclusion, where we state that this makes the situation worse. In these these comments there are already diametrically opposite views on what to do with the default constructors (remove the commented out lines vs. put those lines back and use them). I think this change makes some improvement without causing any regression.

Please using your voting options to indicate if this should not go in. I will explicitly state which suggested changes suggested I am unable to make. At this point I won't have time to revisit most of these files and make a systematic change. If that is better, we could defer this for later. After all, these leaks have not hurt us explicitly and we could (a) decide on  consensus approach and then start making changes or (b) fix issues in a smaller scale with a real problem at hand.

It is becoming difficult to review this code because I can't view the final changes that are being merged in one view.  If others have reviewed this code already, please go ahead.  However, I have a comment because I am unable to decipher from the change.

Are the topN records to be in memory or the topN record keys to be in memory?

TopN records will be in memory as tupps in sql buffer. Record keys is the data structure to perform sort. Once sort is complete followed by all records submitted to parent queue, record keys structure is destroyed.

I personally, forget to change the messages manually when a new message is added/updated.  Perhaps as part of reviews, we should verify that this step is taken.
Is there a JIRA to support the CASCADE option at some point in time; that is, is this something that would be needed to make names more meaningful?

Changes look fine, just a couple of nits.

@robertamarton, there's no JIRA to support CASCADE at the moment. It looks like intent behind CASCADE is for the rename to succeed even if dependent objects exist. If you try a rename now and a view exists, the operation fails with error 1427, "Table cannot be renamed. Reason: Operation not allowed if dependent views exist. Drop the views and recreate them after rename." I can't be completely sure that this is the whole intent, so some definitional work needs to be done before such a JIRA can be written.
